&lt;p&gt;Informing inputs through &lt;strong&gt;arguments&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;flags&lt;/strong&gt; allows the user to automate workflows. It is particularly useful when you&amp;rsquo;re manipulating other tools within a script, as you can automate operations without having to interact with the terminal.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://zupit.github.io/docs-ritchie/docs-ritchie/screen-shot-2020-08-27-at-15.22.10.png&#34; alt=&#34;Executing a formula on Ritchie with Standard Inputs&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Basically, there are two ways to inform input parameters directly on the command lines:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Through the STDIN flag;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Through Input flags.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
